00:25:39,571 --> 00:25:40,606
It's good, right?

498
00:25:41,874 --> 00:25:45,010
There's a burst of umami.

499
00:25:45,444 --> 00:25:48,414
-It's rich in flavor.
-The broth is just incredible.

500
00:25:48,480 --> 00:25:52,851
-And the noodles. The texture is perfect.
-Yes.

501
00:25:53,886 --> 00:25:56,055
It's not too soft, not too firm…

502
00:25:56,121 --> 00:25:58,424
Just that ideal balance
of firmness and softness.

503
00:25:58,490 --> 00:26:01,260
That springiness and firmness…

504
00:26:01,827 --> 00:26:04,997
Would this be similar to Korea's rajuk?

505
00:26:05,064 --> 00:26:07,800
RAJUK, RAMYEON WITH RICE
COOKED TOGETHER IN THE SAME POT

506
00:26:07,866 --> 00:26:09,034
How should I describe this?

507
00:26:09,101 --> 00:26:10,903
Maybe like gaengsigi?

508
00:26:10,969 --> 00:26:12,337
GAENGSIGI, GYEONGSANG-DO DISH

509
00:26:12,404 --> 00:26:14,640
PORRIDGE WITH ANCHOVY BROTH, KIMCHI,
LEFTOVER RICE, ETC.

510
00:26:21,080 --> 00:26:22,581
It's my first time.

511
00:26:23,215 --> 00:26:24,450
I've never had this before.

512
00:26:24,683 --> 00:26:26,151
You can only have pepe-meshi here.

513
00:26:26,218 --> 00:26:28,454
-Did it exist 20 years ago, too?
-It did.

514
00:26:28,520 --> 00:26:31,924
Back then, the younger folks
always ordered pepe-meshi at the end.

515
00:26:31,990 --> 00:26:33,792
I don't really remember eating it, though.

516
00:26:34,927 --> 00:26:36,562
-It's good.
-It's the best.

517
00:26:36,628 --> 00:26:39,164
The umeboshi
really brings it all together.

518
00:26:40,199 --> 00:26:41,733
And the shiso, too.

519
00:26:41,800 --> 00:26:43,335
The shiso and umeboshi.

520
00:27:10,496 --> 00:27:11,730
It's delicious.

521
00:27:13,232 --> 00:27:14,733
It's good, right?

522
00:27:17,202 --> 00:27:21,840
Even without knowing the chef's story,

523
00:27:21,907 --> 00:27:24,076
it would have tasted great,

524
00:27:24,143 --> 00:27:27,312
but after hearing everything
he's been through,

525
00:27:27,379 --> 00:27:28,347
this dish feels like…

526
00:27:29,014 --> 00:27:31,283
-This is Michelin-worthy.
-Michelin?

527
00:27:31,350 --> 00:27:32,885
This is really…

528
00:27:33,485 --> 00:27:35,387
This is the best.

529
00:27:35,454 --> 00:27:37,122
I want to see pepe-meshi

530
00:27:37,189 --> 00:27:40,392
become a national dish someday.

531
00:27:40,926 --> 00:27:43,695
That would be wonderful.

532
00:27:45,597 --> 00:27:47,766
I've been meaning to ask…

533
00:27:48,467 --> 00:27:51,003
when business gets busy,

534
00:27:51,069 --> 00:27:55,007
don't you ever think about expanding?

535
00:27:55,607 --> 00:27:57,743
Making the place

536
00:27:57,809 --> 00:28:00,412
a bit bigger?

537
00:28:00,479 --> 00:28:02,281
Mr. Kuroda, what do you think?

538
00:28:02,347 --> 00:28:03,882
I've thought about it before,

539
00:28:04,283 --> 00:28:07,920
but I believe that requires talent, too.

540
00:28:08,520 --> 00:28:12,558
I don't think I have
that kind of managerial talent.

541
00:28:12,624 --> 00:28:15,427
There was a time I let someone else
run the place for me,

542
00:28:15,494 --> 00:28:17,796
but the quality started to slip
little by little.

543
00:28:17,863 --> 00:28:18,730
Right.

544
00:28:18,797 --> 00:28:21,066
I didn't even know
what I was doing anymore.

545
00:28:21,133 --> 00:28:25,537
So when COVID hit, I shut everything down

546
00:28:25,604 --> 00:28:26,838
and started over on my own.

547
00:28:26,905 --> 00:28:29,308
And honestly, I think the food
tastes much better now.

548
00:28:29,374 --> 00:28:30,943
That makes sense.

549
00:28:31,009 --> 00:28:32,711
So I'm pretty sure

550
00:28:32,778 --> 00:28:35,914
-I'll keep handling everything myself.
-That's cool.

551
00:28:35,981 --> 00:28:38,317
I just want to do what I can,
within my own limits.

552
00:28:40,652 --> 00:28:43,021
What struck me the most earlier was that

553
00:28:43,088 --> 00:28:45,824
he's only got two dishes that use
that sauce, tsukune and rafute,

554
00:28:45,891 --> 00:28:50,562
yet he kept the same sauce alive
all these years.

555
00:28:51,930 --> 00:28:53,332
Isn't that incredible?

556
00:28:53,932 --> 00:28:57,169
If you think of it as your own flavor,

557
00:28:57,236 --> 00:28:59,705
you can't hand it off to others
for the sake of expansion.

558
00:29:00,105 --> 00:29:02,874
It's something you savor right here,
in Mr. Kuroda's little hideout.

559
00:29:02,941 --> 00:29:06,378
-Right.
-The taste of beautiful madness.

560
00:29:06,445 --> 00:29:11,183
If we weren't filming, it's the kind
of place I'd drink myself silly.

561
00:29:12,150 --> 00:29:14,119
It's a precious spot, run by a chef

562
00:29:14,186 --> 00:29:18,390
with real conviction,
someone who's poured years of care

563
00:29:18,490 --> 00:29:21,593
and craftsmanship into his food.

564
00:29:21,660 --> 00:29:23,195
Truly precious.

565
00:29:23,262 --> 00:29:26,031
I feel so grateful

566
00:29:26,098 --> 00:29:28,767
that he introduced me to a place
that serves food this good.

567
00:29:28,834 --> 00:29:30,135
It's honestly amazing.

568
00:29:32,104 --> 00:29:34,706
I was a little worried
it might feel like a burden, though.

569
00:29:34,773 --> 00:29:35,774
For me?

570
00:29:35,841 --> 00:29:39,645
Yes. Revealing
your private spaces like this.

571
00:29:40,379 --> 00:29:41,680
I think

572
00:29:41,747 --> 00:29:46,451
the Netflix viewers are going to love it,

573
00:29:47,786 --> 00:29:50,689
but I did wonder
if that might worry you a bit.

574
00:29:50,756 --> 00:29:52,257
Of course it does.

575
00:29:52,324 --> 00:29:53,191
Right.

576
00:29:53,258 --> 00:29:55,794
-My treasured spots…
-Right.

577
00:29:55,861 --> 00:29:58,397
These secret hideouts
are slowly being discovered by everyone.

578
00:29:58,463 --> 00:30:02,067
I just hope it's not too much pressure
for you, Mr. Matjjigae.

579
00:30:02,134 --> 00:30:04,803
It's not really a burden.

580
00:30:04,870 --> 00:30:07,673
It's all part of fate.

581
00:30:08,707 --> 00:30:12,110
Even if it's a place

582
00:30:12,177 --> 00:30:15,247
I'd rather keep to myself,

583
00:30:15,314 --> 00:30:17,783
if people it interesting,

584
00:30:17,849 --> 00:30:21,987
and want to visit that place
or taste their food,

585
00:30:22,054 --> 00:30:26,558
that can become something valuable
for the restaurant, too.

586
00:30:27,192 --> 00:30:29,795
It's not just mine, after all.

587
00:30:29,861 --> 00:30:33,765
-Yes.
-Somehow, we've ended up with the ability

588
00:30:33,832 --> 00:30:37,235
to share places like this with others.

589
00:30:37,302 --> 00:30:39,037
-Right.
-So,

590
00:30:39,571 --> 00:30:42,374
I hope people seek out
restaurants like this.

591
00:30:44,042 --> 00:30:46,378
They'll think, "But this place
is so hard to find!"

592
00:30:46,445 --> 00:30:50,282
Yet someone's stubbornly making
amazing food there

593
00:30:50,349 --> 00:30:51,516
in a tiny kitchen,

594
00:30:51,583 --> 00:30:55,354
cooking dishes that fit
their own standards.

595
00:30:55,420 --> 00:31:00,325
I think places like that can be found
all over Japan, Korea, and the world.

596
00:31:00,392 --> 00:31:03,095
And it would be wonderful
if we could visit them.

597
00:31:03,161 --> 00:31:04,096
Yes.

598
00:31:05,834 --> 00:31:08,200
AFTER THE FIRST ROUND

599
00:31:10,001 --> 00:31:10,869
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

600
00:31:14,573 --> 00:31:17,109
-We're staying here again tonight.
-Yes, we are.

601
00:31:17,175 --> 00:31:19,077
OMO7 Osaka by Hoshino Resorts

602
00:31:19,144 --> 00:31:22,848
is right in the Shinsekai area,
near Tsutenkaku Tower.

603
00:31:22,914 --> 00:31:25,884
Yes, it's a popular spot
for Korean tourists.

604
00:31:25,951 --> 00:31:27,886
Shinsekai is famous
for kushikatsu, isn't it?

605
00:31:27,953 --> 00:31:31,390
-This area is the mecca of kushikatsu.
-Right.

606
00:31:31,456 --> 00:31:32,324
-Takoyaki.
-Yes.

607
00:31:32,391 --> 00:31:34,192
Okonomiyaki and kushiage.

608
00:31:34,259 --> 00:31:36,762
There are amazing dishes
everywhere in this area.

609
00:31:36,828 --> 00:31:38,830
Right. Takoyaki is the symbol of Osaka.

610
00:31:38,897 --> 00:31:40,999
-Takoyaki, yes.
-And this hotel

611
00:31:41,066 --> 00:31:43,502
actually lets you eat takoyaki inside.

612
00:31:43,568 --> 00:31:45,737
-That's awesome.
-It's a fun little tip.

613
00:31:49,474 --> 00:31:51,476
The takoyaki here has a broth flavor.

614
00:31:53,044 --> 00:31:54,012
It's delicious.

615
00:31:55,347 --> 00:31:57,482
What? Fireworks?

616
00:31:58,617 --> 00:32:01,253
This is basically a date.

617
00:32:01,319 --> 00:32:03,955
It is a date.
Hey, don't sound so disappointed.

618
00:32:04,022 --> 00:32:06,425
-Let's just eat takoyaki.
-A date with a gray-haired senior…

619
00:32:08,593 --> 00:32:09,694
NEXT INSANELY GOOD SPOT

620
00:32:09,761 --> 00:32:10,996
Don't open it.

621
00:32:11,062 --> 00:32:12,197
I want to see it, though.

622
00:32:12,264 --> 00:32:14,466
You have to resist that urge.

623
00:32:14,533 --> 00:32:16,668
-I really want to open it.
-No, don't.

624
00:32:16,735 --> 00:32:19,004
Just let me eat freely, please.
I really want to open it.

625
00:32:23,103 --> 00:32:25,130
ORIGINAL BUDAEJJIGAE

626
